{
  "_comment": "v6.0 - Multi-source bloatware detection (AppX/Provisioned/Registry/WinGet). The audit uses ONE pattern per app entry: 'appx_pattern' when present, else 'name'. Patterns are matched with PowerShell -like against AppX package .Name, provisioned PackageName, registry DisplayName and winget list lines. Microsoft first-party apps use their exact 'Microsoft.*' package name (matches the AppX .Name); third-party / OEM / games use the real publisher-prefixed identifier or a *wildcard* because their package names carry a variable publisher prefix (e.g. Netflix = 4DF9E0F8.Netflix, HP = AD2F1837.*, Lenovo = E046963F.*).",
  "metadata": {
    "version": "6.0",
    "updated": "2026-07-18",
    "detection_sources": ["AppX", "Provisioned", "Registry", "WinGet"],
    "sources_researched": [
      "https://github.com/Raphire/Win11Debloat (App-Removal wiki)",
      "https://patchmypc.com/blog/remove-default-microsoft-store-app-packages-windows11-25h2/"
    ],
    "notes": "Deliberately EXCLUDES genuinely useful/system apps (Calculator, Camera, Photos, Notepad, Paint, Snipping Tool, Store, Terminal, Sticky Notes, Sound Recorder, Quick Assist, Edge, OneDrive) - those are also guarded by protected-packages.json."
  },
